bug.short_desc: Optimization in setting runtime causes missed updates

long_desc.thetext:
The following three methods all have an optimization that causes the call to be ignored if the runtime name matches the existing runtime(s) name: setTargetedRuntimes() setPrimaryRuntime() setRuntime()
This would normally be a great optimization, but the name alone isn't enough to tell if the runtime is currently targeted correctly. Taking the runtime's classpath as an example, it may have become incorrect due to a user change or a change from another tool, or the runtime may have been originally set by another user in a different workspace where the classpath is different.
As a result, calling any of these methods once does not guarantee that the runtime is setup correctly. Callers must 'unset' the runtime first or use another workaround, but this is ugly in the caller's code and means this 'optimization' actually causes code to be twice as slow. :)
The optimization should be done lower in the code, or should check the effects of the call before writing it off as a no-op. These methods shouldn't be called very often, so if the correct optimization can't be found then it might be safer to just leave it off for now. Yet another option would be to keep the optimization for the code that fires the change events, but still allow the lower-level processing like classpath updates to continue (and they can have their own no-op checks).

Could you describe what context you've encountered this problem in? Are you talking about what happens via the Targeted Runtimes property page, the add/remove facets wizard, or via a custom action/button in an adopter product?
It seems to me that at least in some of these contexts the behavior is correct. If the user brings up the Targeted Runtimes property page and doesn't make any changes, then they wouldn't expect any actions to be taken.
The problem of how to handle projects that get corrupted (for whatever reason) can be generalized beyond just the runtime case. Early on we've talked about providing a "project repair" action/button that the user can invoke if they suspect that something about their project got corrupted. That would delegate to all of the facets and let facets correct any corruption to their installations. This would include any runtime-related artifacts in the project (such as classpath entries). This seems to cover the usecases you've described. Do you agree?

A repair option would work for end users, but this problem was caused by the facet API. Adopter code was importing a project or sample and then trying to set the runtime (and therefore classpath). The runtime wasn't changing in this case (it was already correct), so the classpath was never updated and remained invalid (I believe this was because it came from a different workspace).
Given this, the only way to ensure a facet runtime is set correctly is to call the API twice - once to unset the runtime, and once to set it again. You can't really trust it if it says the runtime is already set, since classpath or other settings may be invalid.
The suggestion was that the API should check whether any downstream settings like classpath are correct before deciding that the runtime doesn't need to be set. Using a repair instead would require facets to declare additional API, and there would be additional coding for downstream developers.

> A repair option would work for end users, but this problem was caused > by the facet API. Adopter code was importing a project or sample and > then trying to set the runtime (and therefore classpath). The runtime > wasn't changing in this case (it was already correct), so the classpath > was never updated and remained invalid (I believe this was because > it came from a different workspace).
Well, the repair facility would also be available from API, so adopter code in question could make the required call. This could potentially catch other problems besides runtime classpath issues.
> The suggestion was that the API should check whether any downstream > settings like classpath are correct before deciding that the runtime > doesn't need to be set.
Well, it's really not feasible to check the classpath from the point where the faceted project code has to decide whether to go forward with the change or not. So the suggestion reduced to never checking. This is not a real attractive option and is not the right behavior in all cases. A very similar discussion happend a while ago with respect to facets. There was a request to have facet install delegate for currently-installed facets called every time user runs add/remove facets wizard. The use case, just like in this case, was to allow facets to correct any problem that may exist in facet-related project configuration. That's when the repair idea was first floated, because this needs to be an explicit action rather than an uninteded by-product of something else.
> Using a repair instead would require facets to declare additional API, and > there would be additional coding for downstream developers.
True, but this approach seems better architecturaly. For this particular scenario, I think having jst.java and all the module facets implement the repair callback will be sufficient to fix classpath-related issues.
Yeah, I can default repair logic call facet's runtime_changed delegate (if a facet has one defined) to trick it to make the appropriate changes.

bug.short_desc: ASF report generator can't locate test suites referenced from the workspace

long_desc.thetext:
When using ANT scripts to generate reports, the fileset defined as part of <tptp:publication element must have references from a project inside of a workspace. For exmaple, if a workspace is under "D:\Temp\test-pass" and a test suite is under plug-in/test-suites/JUnitTestSuite.testsuite, then the fileset must be:
<fileset dir="D:\Temp\test-pass\plug-in"> <include name="test-suites/JUnitTestSuite.testsuite" /> </fileset>
If the value of the 'dir' attribute points to a workspace, then the referenced test suite can't be resolved. For example, the following valid fileset will not work:
<fileset dir="D:\Temp\test-pass"> <include name="plug-in/test-suites/JUnitTestSuite.testsuite" /> </fileset>
The output of the ANT script is:
adding file plug-in\test-suites\JUnitTestSuite.testsuite Can not find plug-in\test-suites\JUnitTestSuite.testsuite in workspace.
Also, once this defect is fixed the user shouldn't be forced to specify the property tptp.test.project. Currently not specifying this project name will result in exceptions.
Will fix this in 4.4.

I did further investigation and this limitation is also part of the test execution service.
Specifically in the org.eclipse.hyades.test.core.services.AbstractTestExecutionService.execute() method.
The "results" list containing the relative file path of testsuites assumes that the paths are relative to the project.
Reassigning bug to different component and owner.
Joe if you're not the right person could you reassign this bug.

This was the designed behavior. Before I added the fileset functionality to the execution service, you still needed to specify both the workspace and the project, and the path to the suite was required to be project relative. The superclass of AbstractTestExecutionService has always been AbstractProjectSensitiveService, and all of its subclasses require that the project be specified. AbstractTestResultsPublicationService also extends AbstractProjectSensitiveService.
I wouldn't mind working on this, though I think we'd need to put some thought into the design. I'd suggest it should be an enhancement, butu perhaps it's small enough to treat as a defect.
We use the knowledge of both the workspace and the project when performing these services. In the case of test execution, we need to find the test suite(s) within their project in order to be able to execute them, and in the case of report publicaton, we need to find the test suite within its project so we can query to find the associated execution files. The fileset we pass in needs to be relative to something for us to be able to locate the specified files without recursively searching the entire workspace for each file. Since projects don't necessarily live within the workspace root directory (but still need to be open within the workspacve to be usable), it makes sense for the fileset to be relative to a given project.
I guess the alternative you're suggesting would be for us to change the semantics of the services so that all filesets would be relative to the workspace rather than the project if the project parameter was not specified. I am somewhat concerned that this might further complicate the API, but perhaps it would be more intuitive than I am giving it credit for. I'm interested to hear what you guys think.

My intentions were for the user to be able to freely set the value of the 'dir' attribute to any valid directory structure (a workspace, a project, or even a sub-directory belonging to a project).
It would be nice if the service was smart enough to determine the path of the project using a combination of the path segments specified for the value of the 'dir' attribute and the value of the 'name' attribute for an included entity.
So the short answer is we shouldn't limit the value of the 'dir' attribute to point to a workspace or a project but any directory structure that exists in the workspace (including the workspace itself).

(In reply to comment #5) > So the short answer is we shouldn't limit the value of the 'dir' attribute to > point to a workspace or a project but any directory structure that exists in the > workspace (including the workspace itself).
I don't think I agree with that approach for a couple of reasons. First, it would require searching potentially the entire workspace. Second, I'm not sure it could be made to work unambiguously, because projects can and sometimes do contain other projects within their directories. A good example of this is the TPTP test-results project which, in addition to being a simple project itself, contains lots of other projects as well. If both the test-results project and one of the projects that live within it were present in the workspace, we'd have no way to determine which element to choose (but it matters which one is chosen.)
I can understand the desire to allow a fileset to span projects. What's the motivation for wanting to make the paths in a fileset relative to neither the workspace nor the project? It seems to me that you can do whatever wildcarding you'd want within the fileset anyway, and since all the services in question are workspace relative, I don't really see the usecase.

With how things are currently designed, the user is forced to generate a separate report for each set of test suites belonging to a different project. Providing the ability to allow ‘dir’ to point to a workspace will allow the user to generate one report for all test suites contained in a workspace. If you don’t see any value of allowing ‘dir’ to point to an arbitrary directory, then I would like to see your proposed fix under comment #4.
Thanks Joe.

bug.short_desc: Java runner process leaking named pipes causing process file descriptor limit to be reached.

long_desc.thetext:
Please assign to samwai@ca.us.com
The remote java process launched from the Linux RAC is leaking named pipes. This remote process is the one initiated by Rational Performance Tester whose main class is called RPTRunner and is created by RAServer.
We have detected this by using the /proc facility available on many versions of Linux. The proc facility provides detailed information about each process on the system. For each process on the system, a directory named by its process ID is created under the /proc directory. Under each process there is a directory called fd, which lists every file descriptor. Running ls –la from this directory one can see every open file descriptor and what type of descriptor it is (pipe, socket, or file).
We observe an every increasing number of deleted named pipes to files in /tmp/IBMRAC/UIDXXX. We do not see the RAServer process having open file descriptors to any of these deleted named pipes. This to me implies one side of the named pipe is correctly closing and deleted the pipe while the other is not correctly closing the pipe.
Once the process has more than 1024 file descriptors open any subsequent attempts to create a file descriptor fail (like opening a socket) which causes all sorts of mayhem.
Since the rate of growth is 10-20 a minute, one can use ulimit -n to increase the file descriptor limit.
Samson, this looks to be in the java side AC APIs. Can you please take a look?
Can you check if your agent is calling RemoteComponentSkeleton.deregister()? Calling this method will supposingly clean up the agent named pipe.
While waiting for Richard's response on whether deregister() is called, I will retarget this to 4.2.1.1 for now.

Results of RemoteComponentSkeleton.deregister() test running RPT7.0 running TPTP4.2.1 on Linux.
Deregister is getting called, but at the end of the test. See attachment details#1.
Note: the problem we are seeing is not that the named pipes are not getting cleaned up at the end of the session but growing during it. It looks like the process is creating a series of named pipe file descriptors most of them pointing to the same named pipe.
If you look in the attachment details#2 area. I show the output of /proc/{PID}/fd/. This shows the process holding onto fds, some of which have been deleted.
If you look at details#3 area, you can see the rate of growth at about 10 fds per 50 seconds.
Repeatable every time.
Created an attachment (id=53508) Results of a RemoteComponent Test

Just an idea, would it be possible to instrument the native porition of the code creating the FIFO or opening it and print out the file descriptor coming back. If we are leaking then we would see the fd number increasing.

Richard, do you have the build ID of the RAC driver you were using? I think the fix for bug 159179 (same as bug 163947) supposed to have fixed the FD problem you are seeing. If you are using the "patched" driver I hand-built for Kevin/Joe/Todd before then most likely it is not address in bug 159179.

Created an attachment (id=53556) Instrumented RAC
The RAServer process will print lots of debug messages on the console. The agent side debug messages will be piped to the file "/tmp/hcbnd.dbg".
I have attached hcbnd.dbg generated from your debug files. These modules have fixed the fd leak and I consider this fixed. What version of TPTP will this RAC appear in?
Created an attachment (id=53566) RAC debug output

From the debug output provided, it seems to me that the FD is not leaking as badly as before. Can you confirm?
The instrumented RAC contains the latest fixes.
Confirmed. See comment #9.

The FD problem has been fixed under bug 163947 and has been delivered to TPTP 4.2.1.1. RPT will need to pick up the 4.2.1.1 driver to get this fix.

Reproduced this issue today:
* Start fresh installed eclipse-SDK-3.2.1 on WinXP * Software Updates > Find and Install > New Remote Site http://download.eclipse.org/dsdp/tm/signedUpdates * Select RSE Runtime / Core and ssh --> remotecdt is not required, as described earlier * Install All: when prompted by dialog, let Eclipse restart * Software Updates > Find and Install > same site as before * Select RSE Runtime / FTP * UM downloads files, "signed feature" dialog is shown * Press "Install All" button
--> Installation aborts with an "Internal Error" --> .log file attached
What's interesting is that I could NOT reproduce the issue on eclipse-3.2.1-linux-gtk, when I went to the same update site, selected ALL features there and installed all of them at once. It appears to be necessary that 2 features are installed first, Eclipse is restarted then, and then the other feature is installed.

I was finally able to track this down:
* The problem is only with the signed and packed jar, so it only happens with an 1.5 JVM, because only with 1.5 JVM will load the .jar.pack.gz file (1.4 will load the signed but not packed .jar file). That's the reason why I could not reproduce it on linux-gtk in comment 2, because I was running that under an 1.4 jvm.
* The NPE happens in Update Manager because the signed, packed, nested jar is considered corrupt, but in CertVerifier.alreadyValidated() the status IVerificationResult.CORRUPT is not considered. So, it tries to access the root certificate which is not set (==null) in case the jar is considered corrupt.
So, summing up -- I was providing the UM with a corrupt jar (see bug 135044 comment 56), but the UM should handle the corrupt jar more gracefully -- it should tell me which entry of the jar is considered corrupt, instead of bailing out with a NullPointerException.
The fix should be easy by considering IVerificationResult.CORRUPT in CertVerifier.alreadyValidated().

Sorry for the confusion -- this is talking about a signed, packed bundle that contains a nested jar. Updated the summary accordingly.
Made another test: with the latest and greatest jarprocessor, I added META-INF/eclipse.inf specifying jarprocessor.exclude.children.sign=true
I had expected that this would force the sign script to sign the nested jarfile in its binary form. But after a repack, sign, pack, unpack, operation, jarsigner -verify claims that the nested jar were corrupt. Is this a bug in the sign script after all?

Workaround: I finally got my jars to install as signed bundle with the following entries in META-INF/eclipse.inf:
#do not sign individual entries of nested jars; sign the archive as a whole #instead; also do not pack until bug [163421] is resolved jarprocessor.exclude.children.pack = true jarprocessor.exclude.children.sign = true
The disadvantage of this is, that the nested jar is not pack200'ed so my bundles are now 160K instead of 50K to download.
My feeling is that the problem occurs because of the following: * Outer and inner nested jar are repacked (conditioned) * Outer and inner jar are signed * Because of signing the inner jar, many new strings are in the inner Jar's META-INF/Manifest.mf file, so the Stringtable changes; this leads pack200 to pack differently * When the signed inner jar is now packed and expanded, this step is not lossless any more, because the signed (modified) jar is not conditioned any more. So, the signature verification of the binary nested jar fails.
In order to fix this, I think the "sign" script would need to have an additional option like "-repackAll" that does the following: 1. condition nested jar 2. sign nested jar 3. condition nested jar again 4. now sign the outer jar, including the binary nested jar
It appears that currently step (3) is missing and because of that the verification fails.

bug.short_desc: Add methods to check item visibility in Tables and Trees

long_desc.thetext:
There is currently no way to check if a TableItem (or a TreeItem) is in the visible area of its parent and how many item a widget can display.
This would allow to clear items and dispose images when they are not visible, in order to reduce the memory and handle usage.
My use case : I'm working on a photo sharing application in which i display a lot of different images (3000+) in a table and in a custom widget. These widgets are both using the SWT.VIRTUAL mode, but I don't want to have too many images in memory in the same time, so I have to dispose them when they are not used anymore. (see http://sharemedia.free.fr/features.php?lang=en)
With the current API, I had to use a kind of cache with a limited size (about 40 images for the table and 200 for my custom widget). I catch the Paint event on each item and i add the image in the cache if it was not already in it. When the cache reaches its limit, the oldest image is diposed.
This works great, but only when the number of visible item is lower than the cache capacity. In this last case, each image is disposed and created again when a paint event occurs : everything become far too slow. (The number of displayed items change with the screen resolution and the window / view size). As a workaround , I increased the cache size, but I often have 40+200 images in memory when only 20 are visible.
The API enhancements that could help in the case are : - A way to get how many items a table can display in its curent size. - A method that check if an item is in the visible area of its parent. - maybe visible/invisible events which fire when an item's state changes.

Of course, this method would be useless if the table widget has to do the same calculation on each call, but I think that value is somehow calculated internaly by the table on redraw.

bug.short_desc: publishing a Web Service, why each package must map a distinct namespace?

long_desc.thetext: When publishing a Web Service,I choice "mapping package to namespace". In next page,I insert into mappings as below: com.huawei.gateway.soap.facade --> http://impl.prbt.com com.huawei.gateway.soap.model --> http://impl.prbt.com and so on. When submit, I got an error message such as "namespace duplicated"! Why? I will map more than one packages to only one namespace!I'm so discouraged that I must reopen JBuilder 2005 and do things remaining! I suggest Eclipse enhances the default as early as possiable! Thanks a lot! Yours, Jin Jiankang from huawei corp. China

Jin, thanks, however, this is not so much an Eclipse WTP issue as it is a consequence of how Apache Axis accomplishes bottom-up generation and deployment of Web services.
When starting with Java, Eclipse WTP drives the Axis "Java2WSDL" emitter followed by the "WSDL2Java" emitter, very much as would be done manually according to Axis' documentation [1] on building Web services from Java. Java2WSDL produces WSDL from your service class, while WSDL2Java produces the deployment information (deploy.wsdd) necessary for you service class to run under the Axis servlet.
The mapping of multiple packages to a common namespace via "Java2WSDL" is, by itself, OK. Problems begin however when driving "WSDL2Java" to generate the deployment data. The "WSDL2Java" emitter does not provide any way to apply the inverse mapping of a single namespace (eg. http://impl.prbt.com) to multiple packages (eg. com.huawei.gateway.soap.facade vs. com.huawei.gateway.soap.model). The WSDL2Java emitter would require explicit knowledge of the original Java service class and/or how the WSDL was generated from it via Java2WSDL in order to invert the mapping correctly, or WSDL2Java would have to support XML-to-Java mappings that include the local name (which maps to the class' basename).
You should consider opening a JIRA to have this pattern supported [2] by the Axis emitters. Meanwhile, we'll investigate whether we can work around this in WTP. If you or anyone you know is interested in contributing a solution, this would certainly help speed things up.
Thanks, CB.
[1] http://ws.apache.org/axis/java/user-guide.html#Java2WSDLBuildingWSDLFromJava [2] http://ws.apache.org/axis/bugs.html
No plan to fix in WTP. If you want to pursue it further, please open a JIRA for Apache Axis.

bug.short_desc: [quick fix] Delete unused method quickfix also deleting non-javadoc comment before method

long_desc.thetext: Delete unused method quickfix in Java editor (i.e. for unused private methods) also deleting non-javadoc comment before method (both /* */ and // comments, even those that are separated by an empty line from the method).

When removing methods we remove up to the next method to avoid that a file ends up with comment artifacts.
I know this is a heuristic that might be good in one case but bad in another. No changes planed here.

Please consider or improve your heuristic. You can at least provide an option to disable this heuristic and only delete non-line comment (javadoc and non-javadoc) that prepend a method without any empty lines in between.
Current quickfix can silently remove commented out method and it is really hard to notice, especially if code folding is used along with this.
Sorry, this is quite a fundamental change that would cause several ripples and is considerable work. Not planed, sorry.

Am I asking something unreasonable? If you can't do it immediately, please mark it for later.
PS: you can also detect line breaks between method and comments and issue a warning, so user will be aware of the deletion instead of silently loosing code.
It's reasonable, but not on the top propority list.

bug.short_desc: org.eclipse.core.runtime should use Import-Package instead of Require-Bundle

long_desc.thetext: org.eclipse.core.runtime uses Import-Package instead of Require-Bundle. These should be switched to Require-Bundle. Especially the org.eclipse.osgi bundle reference is important for the eRCP project to achieve the replacable OSGi framework item.
I believe you have this backwards. You are actualy requesting that the runtime bundle be changed to use import package for at least the org.eclipse.osgi references.
Yes, you are correct! It was not a good idea to file reports late in the afternoon after all.

There is some ongoing work to make this possible with the supplement bundle, but there are some issues with the API that org.eclipse.core.runtime offers. The runtime bundle currently reexports the org.eclipse.osgi bundle. This means any bundle that requires org.eclipse.core.runtime will get access to all packages exported by org.eclipse.osgi. This includes all the org.osgi.* and org.eclipse.osgi.* packages that the framework exports and any packages exported by the vm execution environment.
A change in the packages that are available when requiring the org.eclipse.core.runtime bundle is probably breaking API. We may be able to work around these types of issues using optional bundle requirements.

In addition to the comment 3, here is the full list of bundles re-exported by the runtime plugin: org.eclipse.osgi org.eclipse.equinox.common org.eclipse.core.jobs org.eclipse.equinox.registry org.eclipse.equinox.preferences org.eclipse.core.contenttype
The re-exports are needed to support backward compatibility. On another hand, Import-Packages can't be re-exported (there is no such capability in OSGi and, IMHO, it would be quite messy if there were one).
Closing the bug as there is nothing we can do here.
(This is likely going to apply to other plugins that use bundle re-export and have to maintain backward compatibility.)

As to the original problem of using Eclipse runtime in an RCP application in a different OSGi environment:
The long-term goal is that org.eclipse.core.runtime plugin is going to be left only for the backward compatibility with all functionlaity available from separate bundles such as org.eclipse.core.jobs, org.eclipse.equinox.registry, and org.eclipse.equinox.preferences, etc.
In fact, this is close to what we have today. The major portion of the org.eclipse.core.runtime is re-exported from [smaller] org.eclipse.core.* and org.eclispe.equinox.* bundles.
While we are not 100% where, the intention is to make all RCP-relevant functionality available without the org.eclipse.core.runtime. Hopefully, this will resolve the original problems described in this bug.

bug.short_desc: [Field Assist] - API - ControlDecoration should work with image+text, not FieldDecoration

long_desc.thetext:
DecoratedField supported multiple decoration locations, so it was useful to expose a data structure that referred to a particular decoration. Hence FieldDecoration was defined. It is just an image+text data structure, but was useful for asking DecoratedField to "do things" to a particular decoration, such as hiding it, showing it, updating it, etc.
The initial API for ControlDecoration also supported FieldDecoration, in an attempt to "explain itself" as being similar to DecoratedField. However, since a ControlDecoration only shows one decoration, there's not really a need for the image+text to have any kind of identity.
It would be better if the ControlDecoration API worked in terms of having an image and a description text. Clients could still use FieldDecorations and the registry if desired, but the API shouldn't require it, since it's trivial to pull the image and text out of a decoration and feed it to ControlDecoration.

bug.short_desc: Need obfuscation support

long_desc.thetext: This isn't due in 0.7, but this bug is to track the need for obfuscation support in MTJ to reduce the size of deployed jar files.
See the latest implementation -a

This code points at enabled third-party code that it assumes is installed in E:\MTJ_root\Obfuscate. This code should not be enabled by default since it is using 3rd party code, and using a default location. Look at the security code for an example of what we did to allow the user to configure to use an add-on. Are we making API calls, and do we need legal approval for this code.
Please Kevin, send details on that. The obfuscators are using preferences to point to the external jar.

Look at the security modules. We provide the preferece, but do not point at something that is not installed. If the user wants to enable the function, since it is third-party, they must configure the code to point at the installation.
If you are pointing at a jar, you are making API calls. If you are making API calls, you should get legal approval to call the APIs.

As currently we do have other components that do allow the user to download other external components and the usage happens only after that. (like Nokia PC Suite) Please see the mtj-home\docs\MTJ Obfuscation wrapper.ppt The Obfuscation does not use in any way the external components, instead the user has to configure the local location to get it working.
It's nice that you are taking actions on this area and please continue. If you feel that there is a need to get it legally approved, so please go forward.
-Arto

Arto if you are accessing a jar, it needs legal approval. Since you added the code you need to follow through with it or remove the code. Technically, it should not have been checked in without preliminary approval, and we definitely can not release with it.

According to the "MTJ Obfuscation wrapper.ppt" document, the user installs the obfuscator by herself and is not in anyway hardcoded to our source. The reference to E:\MTJ_root\Obfuscate is not in the source code but some development time configuration which is stored to configuration file. That will not be in the build.

The question is, is the code added making API calls to a class library that is added to a java process, or is it building a command line and launching an executable. If it is the former, it needs legal approval. If it is the latter, it is probably ok, but you should check with legal.
The point about the command line entry, is that the configuration file contains bogus data. I suggested that Arto look at the existing security code and match the functionality there, where a bogus location is not prepopulated, and we maintain consistency with our existing code.
Also, thanks for checking in the document you referenced.

It is question of launching external app. from command line. Later on the user may add what ever preferred obfuscator she might use. We are not able to check all the available products and it is not feasible as e.g. versions will change. In initial state there aren't any obfuscators and user must add them by themselves. The clean MTJ installation doesn't have links to any obfuscators.
